04243nam a22005775i 9780774859561DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20082007xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748595617 a10.59962/97807748595612doi  a(DE-B1597)662041  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1090.7.C2.D85 2007eb 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.311 aDummitt, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Manly Modern :bMasculinity in Postwar Canada /cChristopher Dummitt. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSexuality Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Manly Modern -- tComing Home -- tAt Work -- tIn the Mountains -- tBefore the Courts and on the Couch -- tOn the Road -- tConclusion: Manly Modernism in Hindsight -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow did one act like a modern man in postwar Canada? With a great deal of difficulty. During the Great Depression and Second World War, many men were first out of work and then away from their families. After the war came attempts to re-establish the traditional gender hierarchy by emphasizing men's modernity, allegedly superior rationality, and ability to handle risk, but the strategy had contradictory repercussions. The Manly Modern: Masculinity in Postwar Canada traces the history of what happened when men's supposed modernity became one of their defining features. Through a series of case studies covering such diverse subjects as car culture, mountaineering, war veterans, murder trials, and a bridge collapse, Christopher Dummitt argues that the very idea of what it meant to be modern was gendered. A strong current of anti-modernist sentiment bubbled just beneath the surface of postwar masculinity, creating rumblings about the state of modern manhood that, ironically, mirrored the tensions that burst forth in 1960s gender radicalism. The first major book on the history of masculinity in Canada, The Manly Modern will appeal to scholars and students in history, gender studies, and cultural studies, as well as to readers interested in the history and social construction of gender.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMasculinityxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aMasculinityxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMenzBritish ColumbiazVancouverxSocial conditionsy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aMenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485956140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774859561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774859561/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles